## Reading

ASER assessments are conducted in the household. The type of school in which children are enrolled (government or private) is also recorded.

### Table 6: % Children by grade and reading level
All children 2016

| Std | Not even letters | Can recognize letters | Can read simple text | Can read Std II level text | Can read Std V level text | Total |
|-----|------------------|-----------------------|----------------------|----------------------------|---------------------------|-------|
| I   | 42.1             | 25.3                  | 20.5                 | 10.1                       | 2.0                       | 100   |
| II  | 15.2             | 18.4                  | 35.6                 | 22.8                       | 8.0                       | 100   |
| III | 6.5              | 10.2                  | 28.5                 | 38.2                       | 16.6                      | 100   |
| IV  | 3.2              | 5.8                   | 18.5                 | 42.5                       | 30.0                      | 100   |
| V   | 1.8              | 3.5                   | 12.5                 | 35.2                       | 47.0                      | 100   |
| VI  | 1.2              | 2.5                   | 8.5                  | 28.5                       | 59.3                      | 100   |
| VII | 0.8              | 1.8                   | 5.5                  | 22.5                       | 69.4                      | 100   |
| VIII| 0.5              | 1.2                   | 3.5                  | 18.5                       | 76.3                      | 100   |

Each row shows the variation in children's reading levels within a given grade. For example, among children in Std III, 6.5% cannot even recognize letters, 10.2% can recognize letters but cannot read simple text, 28.5% can read simple text but cannot read Std II level text, 38.2% can read Std II level text but cannot read Std V level text, and 16.6% can read Std V level text. For each grade, the total of these exclusive categories is 100%.

