## Arithmetic

ASER assessments are conducted in the household. The type of school in which children are enrolled (government or private) is also recorded.

### Table 9: % Children by grade and arithmetic level
All children 2016

| Std | Not even 1-9 | Recognize numbers 1-9 | Recognize numbers 10-99 | Subtract | Divide | Total |
|-----|---------------|------------------------|--------------------------|----------|--------|-------|
| I   | 35.5          | 30.2                   | 25.5                     | 6.5      | 2.3    | 100   |
| II  | 12.5          | 18.5                   | 45.2                     | 18.5     | 5.3    | 100   |
| III | 5.5           | 8.5                    | 35.5                     | 35.5     | 15.0   | 100   |
| IV  | 2.5           | 4.5                    | 25.5                     | 42.5     | 25.0   | 100   |
| V   | 1.5           | 3.5                    | 20.5                     | 38.5     | 36.0   | 100   |
| VI  | 1.2           | 2.5                    | 18.5                     | 35.5     | 42.3   | 100   |
| VII | 0.8           | 1.5                    | 15.5                     | 32.5     | 49.7   | 100   |
| VIII| 0.5           | 1.2                    | 12.5                     | 28.5     | 57.3   | 100   |

Each row shows the variation in children's arithmetic levels within a given grade. For example, among children in Std III, 5.5% cannot even recognize numbers 1-9, 8.5% can recognize numbers up to 9 but cannot recognize numbers up to 99 or higher, 35.5% can recognize numbers up to 99 but cannot do subtraction, 35.5% can do subtraction but cannot do division, and 15.0% can do division. For each grade, the total of these exclusive categories is 100%.

